Analyzing Land Use and Fires in California¶

I am from the Sierra Nevada and Lake Tahoe area, so I am particularly interested in how fires are affecting different ecosystems and land uses. I thought exploring fire data more closely would be a good exercise for learning Python and how to extract/transform/load data using the ArcGIS API for Python, Arcpy, and Pandas libraries, conducting various tabular and spatial analyses, plotting and graphing results, and illustrating key findings.

🔥💻🏡

Now I want to export my cleaned 2011 Spatial DataFrame as a feature class. I was having an issue with incompatible data types exporting to feature classes (objects and categories must be converted to strings), so I found an Esrsi community solution where someone was kind enough to write a function to fix the issue. I've used that function here. We love open source 😁

In [12]:
# From Esri Community Solution:
def convert_dtypes_arcgis(df):
  # Convert dataframe dtypes which are not compatible with ArcGIS
  # Use builtin Pandas dtype conversion
  df = df.convert_dtypes(infer_objects=True)
  # Then str convert any remaining special object/category fields 
  for col in df.columns:
    # print(col, '/', df[col].dtype)
    if df[col].dtype == 'object' or df[col].dtype == 'category':
      df[col] = df[col].astype('str')
  # Return modified df
  return df
In [13]:
sdf_fires_2011 = sdf_fires_2011.replace(np.nan,0) # when we go to export this as a feature class, we cannot have any null values
sdf_fires_2011 = convert_dtypes_arcgis(sdf_fires_2011) # use the function above to convert all incompatible data types to strings!

Land Use¶

Next I want to explore land uses. Land use data obtained from USGS, titled: GAP/LANDFIRE National Terrestrial Ecosystems 2011. I want to understand which land use types are most common in zones that have burned. To do this, I used the Zonal Statistics as Table tool in arcpy. First lets take a look at an image of the .tif because it cannot be mapped in a widget without a license.

It shows us the variation in spectral imagery, but in order to get the values we have to load our .tif into a file geodatabase. Once that's done, we can use the raster as an input for the zonal statistics tool.

In [16]:
# GAP/LANDFIRE National Terrestrial Ecosystems 2011 data in a fgdb
landuse = r'C:/Users/IYOUNGS/Documents/ArcGIS/Projects/MyProject/MyProject.gdb/gaplf2011lc_v30_ca'

# generate zonal statistics where the land use types are the zones 
# the sum is the number of acres burned in the land use type
zonal_table = arcpy.ia.ZonalStatisticsAsTable(landuse, "VALUE", "fires_raster", "zonal_statistics", "DATA", "SUM")

To get a table in a file geodatabase into a Pandas DataFrame, I used this function from David Wasserman on Github! 😁

In [17]:
def arcgis_table_to_df(in_fc, input_fields=None, query=""):
    """Function will convert an arcgis table into a pandas dataframe with an object ID index, and the selected
    input fields using an arcpy.da.SearchCursor.
    :param - in_fc - input feature class or table to convert
    :param - input_fields - fields to input to a da search cursor for retrieval
    :param - query - sql query to grab appropriate values
    :returns - pandas.DataFrame"""
    OIDFieldName = arcpy.Describe(in_fc).OIDFieldName
    if input_fields:
        final_fields = [OIDFieldName] + input_fields
    else:
        final_fields = [field.name for field in arcpy.ListFields(in_fc)]
    data = [row for row in arcpy.da.SearchCursor(in_fc,final_fields,where_clause=query)]
    fc_dataframe = pd.DataFrame(data,columns=final_fields)
    fc_dataframe = fc_dataframe.set_index(OIDFieldName,drop=True)
    return fc_dataframe

What are the top ecosystems that burn by acreage?

In [20]:
zonal_keys = zonal.merge(keys, left_on='VALUE', right_on='Value', how = 'left') # merge the keys to the zonal statistics table

# sort the values by sum of acres burned and subset the top 10
top_area_burned = zonal_keys.sort_values('SUM', ascending = False)[:10].reset_index() 

# set up parameters for the plot
x = top_area_burned['ECOLSYS_LU']
y = top_area_burned['SUM']

plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
plt.barh(x, y, color = 'red')
plt.xlabel("Sum of Acreage")
plt.title("Most fires (by acre) happen in Coastal Grassland")
plt.show()
